The paper deals with video object detection and proposes novel tracking-based perspectives for evaluating the temporal performance of detectors. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also proposes tubelet refinement for improving detectors' performance, which involves machine learning techniques and optimization, indicating that it could also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also deals with multi-object tracking (MOT) and proposes a unified framework for video object detection, MOT, and single object tracking (SOT), suggesting that it could belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Finally, the paper conducts experiments on the ImageNet VID dataset, which is a popular dataset for video object detection and tracking, indicating that it could also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
